            overview: "Probability quantifies uncertainty. Bayes Theorem describes how to update beliefs given evidence. In ML, probability underpins Naive Bayes classifiers, Bayesian inference, probabilistic graphical models, uncertainty estimation, and reinforcement learning.",
            problemStatement: "Machine learning models must make decisions under uncertainty. Without probability theory, we can't quantify prediction confidence, update models with new data, or make optimal decisions under ambiguous conditions.",
            intuitionFirst: "Probability is common sense reduced to numbers. If it is cloudy (evidence), rain is more likely (posterior probability). Bayes Theorem formalizes this: P(rain|clouds) = P(clouds|rain)*P(rain)/P(clouds).",
            realLifeAnalogy: "A doctor interprets a test result: If a disease affects 1% of people (prior), and the test is 99% accurate (likelihood), and you test positive, Bayes theorem tells you the probability you actually have the disease is only about 50%. This counterintuitive result explains why follow-up tests matter.",
            howItWorks: "P(A|B) = P(B|A)P(A)/P(B). Prior P(A): initial belief. Likelihood P(B|A): how probable evidence is if hypothesis is true. Evidence P(B): overall probability of seeing the evidence. Posterior P(A|B): updated belief after seeing evidence.",
            beginnerExample: "# P(disease|positive) calculation\n# Disease prevalence: 1% -> P(D) = 0.01\n# Test accuracy: 99% -> P(Pos|D) = 0.99, P(Pos|not D) = 0.01\n\np_d = 0.01  # Prior\np_pos_given_d = 0.99  # Likelihood\np_pos_given_not_d = 0.01\np_not_d = 1 - p_d\n\n# Evidence: P(Pos) = P(Pos|D)P(D) + P(Pos|not D)P(not D)\nevidence = p_pos_given_d * p_d + p_pos_given_not_d * p_not_d\n\n# Posterior: P(D|Pos)\np_d_given_pos = (p_pos_given_d * p_d) / evidence\nprint(f'P(disease | positive) = {p_d_given_pos:.2%}')\n# ~= 50% - surprisingly low!",
            intermediateExample: "import numpy as np\nfrom sklearn.naive_bayes import GaussianNB\nfrom sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score\n\nnp.random.seed(42)\nn_samples = 1000\n\nX_class0 = np.random.multivariate_normal([0, 0], [[1, 0], [0, 1]], n_samples // 2)\nX_class1 = np.random.multivariate_normal([2, 3], [[1.5, 0], [0, 1.5]], n_samples // 2)\nX = np.vstack([X_class0, X_class1])\ny = np.hstack([np.zeros(n_samples // 2), np.ones(n_samples // 2)])\n\nclf = GaussianNB()\nscores = cross_val_score(clf, X, y, cv=5)\nprint(f'Accuracy: {scores.mean():.3f} +/- {scores.std():.3f}')\n\nclf.fit(X, y)\nprobs = clf.predict_proba(np.array([[1, 1.5]]))\nprint(f'Class probabilities: {probs[0]}')",
            productionExample: "import numpy as np\nfrom sklearn.naive_bayes import MultinomialNB\nfrom sklearn.feature_extraction.text import TfidfVectorizer\nfrom sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline\n\nclass SpamClassifier:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self.pipeline = Pipeline([\n            ('vectorizer', TfidfVectorizer(max_features=10000, stop_words='english')),\n            ('classifier', MultinomialNB(alpha=1.0))\n        ])\n\n    def fit(self, texts: list[str], labels: list[int]):\n        self.pipeline.fit(texts, labels)\n\n    def predict_proba(self, texts: list[str]) -> np.ndarray:\n        return self.pipeline.predict_proba(texts)\n\n    def top_spam_indicators(self, n: int = 10) -> list[str]:\n        feature_names = self.pipeline.named_steps['vectorizer'].get_feature_names_out()\n        log_probs = self.pipeline.named_steps['classifier'].feature_log_prob_\n        log_odds = log_probs[1] - log_probs[0]\n        top_indices = np.argsort(log_odds)[-n:][::-1]\n        return [feature_names[i] for i in top_indices]",
