            performanceNotes: "R^2 is a normalized metric (0-1 range in most cases), making it easier to communicate to non-technical stakeholders.",
            securityNotes: "R^2 can be artificially inflated by data leakage. Always compute R^2 on a holdout set. R^2 can hide subgroup performance.",
            comparisonTable: "| Metric | Range | Interpretable? | Scale-independent? | Use Case |\n|--------|-------|---------------|-------------------|----------|\n| R^2 | (-inf, 1] | Yes (proportion) | Yes | Model comparison |\n| Adjusted R^2 | (-inf, 1] | Yes (penalized) | Yes | Feature selection |\n| RMSE | [0, inf) | Original units | No | Absolute error |\n| MAE | [0, inf) | Original units | No | Robust error |",
            codingExamples: "import numpy as np\nfrom sklearn.metrics import r2_score\n\ndef weighted_r2(y_true, y_pred, weights):\n    weighted_mean = np.average(y_true, weights=weights)\n    ss_res = np.sum(weights * (y_true - y_pred) ** 2)\n    ss_tot = np.sum(weights * (y_true - weighted_mean) ** 2)\n    return 1 - ss_res / ss_tot\n\n# Variance inflation factor (detect multicollinearity)\ndef variance_inflation_factor(X):\n    vifs = []\n    for i in range(X.shape[1]):\n        y = X[:, i]\n        X_other = np.delete(X, i, axis=1)\n        model = LinearRegression().fit(X_other, y)\n        r2 = r2_score(y, model.predict(X_other))\n        vifs.append(1 / (1 - r2))\n    return np.array(vifs)",
