            bestPractices: "Use ComplementNB for imbalanced text classification. Use log-probabilities internally. Apply feature selection to remove irrelevant words. Use TF-IDF instead of raw counts for better performance.",
            performanceNotes: "Naive Bayes is among the fastest classifiers. Training is O(n*d) and prediction is O(d). It is linearly scalable to millions of samples and features. Perfect for online learning (partial_fit).",
            codingExamples: "import numpy as np\n\n# Gaussian Naive Bayes from scratch\nclass GaussianNBScratch:\n    def fit(self, X, y):\n        self.classes = np.unique(y)\n        self.means = {}\n        self.stds = {}\n        self.priors = {}\n        for c in self.classes:\n            X_c = X[y == c]\n            self.means[c] = X_c.mean(axis=0)\n            self.stds[c] = X_c.std(axis=0) + 1e-9\n            self.priors[c] = len(X_c) / len(X)\n        return self\n\n    def _pdf(self, x, mean, std):\n        return np.exp(-0.5 * ((x - mean) / std)**2) / (std * np.sqrt(2 * np.pi))\n\n    def predict_proba(self, X):\n        probs = []\n        for x in X:\n            class_probs = []\n            for c in self.classes:\n                likelihood = np.prod(self._pdf(x, self.means[c], self.stds[c]))\n                class_probs.append(likelihood * self.priors[c])\n            probs.append(np.array(class_probs) / sum(class_probs))\n        return np.array(probs)\n\n    def predict(self, X):\n        return np.argmax(self.predict_proba(X), axis=1)",
