            howItWorks: "sigma(z) = 1/(1+e^-z). Derivative: sigma'(z) = sigma(z)*(1-sigma(z)). Maximum derivative at z=0 (0.25). Near zero derivative for large |z| (saturation - causes vanishing gradients). In practice: sigma(z) > 0.5 -> class 1, sigma(z) < 0.5 -> class 0.",
            beginnerExample: "import numpy as np\n\ndef sigmoid(z):\n    return 1 / (1 + np.exp(-np.clip(z, -500, 500)))\n\ndef sigmoid_derivative(z):\n    s = sigmoid(z)\n    return s * (1 - s)\n\nz = np.array([-10, -5, -1, 0, 1, 5, 10])\nprint(f'z:     {z}')\nprint(f'sig:   {sigmoid(z)}')\nprint(f'derv:  {sigmoid_derivative(z)}')\n\n# At z=0, sigmoid = 0.5 (uncertain)\n# At z=10, sigmoid ~= 1 (very certain yes)\n# At z=-10, sigmoid ~= 0 (very certain no)",
