            overview: "Statistical anomaly detection uses distributional assumptions: Z-score for Gaussian data, IQR for robust outlier detection, and Grubbs' test for hypothesis testing of outliers.",
            problemStatement: "Sometimes you need simple, interpretable, and statistically rigorous anomaly detection without complex models. Statistical methods provide p-values and confidence intervals.",
            intuitionFirst: "If a data point is more than 3 standard deviations from the mean, it's likely an anomaly. For skewed data, use IQR (percentile-based) instead.",
            realLifeAnalogy: "In a class of students, if one student scored 5 standard deviations above the mean, that's suspicious - likely cheating or gifted. Need to investigate.",
            howItWorks: "Z-score: (x - mean)/std. |Z| > 3 = anomaly. IQR method: Q1 - 1.5*IQR and Q3 + 1.5*IQR thresholds. Modified Z-score: uses median and MAD for robustness. Grubbs' test: sequential hypothesis testing for outliers.",
            beginnerExample: "import numpy as np\nfrom scipy import stats\ndata = np.random.randn(100)\ndata[0] = 10  # outlier\nz_scores = np.abs(stats.zscore(data))\nprint(f'Z-score outliers: {np.where(z_scores > 3)[0]}')\nQ1, Q3 = np.percentile(data, [25, 75])\nIQR = Q3 - Q1\nlower, upper = Q1 - 1.5*IQR, Q3 + 1.5*IQR\nprint(f'IQR outliers: {np.where((data < lower) | (data > upper))[0]}')",
            intermediateExample: "def detect_outliers_multi_method(data):\n    methods = {}\n    methods['zscore'] = np.abs(stats.zscore(data)) > 3\n    methods['modified_zscore'] = np.abs(data - np.median(data)) / (1.4826 * stats.median_abs_deviation(data)) > 3.5\n    Q1, Q3 = np.percentile(data, [25, 75])\n    IQR = Q3 - Q1\n    methods['iqr'] = (data < Q1 - 1.5*IQR) | (data > Q3 + 1.5*IQR)\n    return {k: np.where(v)[0].tolist() for k, v in methods.items()}",
            productionExample: "class StatisticalOutlierDetector:\n    def __init__(self, method='iqr', threshold=3):\n        self.method = method; self.threshold = threshold\n    def fit(self, X): pass\n    def predict(self, X):\n        if self.method == 'zscore':\n            scores = np.abs(stats.zscore(X, nan_policy='omit'))\n        elif self.method == 'iqr':\n            Q1, Q3 = np.percentile(X, [25, 75]); IQR = Q3 - Q1\n            lower, upper = Q1 - 1.5*IQR, Q3 + 1.5*IQR\n            return ((X < lower) | (X > upper)).astype(int)\n        return (scores > self.threshold).astype(int)",
